

<section>
  <title>Additional Problems</title>
  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <idx><h>convergence</h><h> of a sequence</h><h>implies the convergence of the absolute sequence</h></idx>
    Prove that if
        <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}s_n=s</m> then <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}|s_n|=|s|</m>.
        Prove that the converse is true when <m>s=0</m>,
        but it is not necessarily true otherwise.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
            <idx><h>sequences</h><h>limit is unique</h></idx>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>\left(s_n\right)</m> and
              <m>\left(t_n\right)</m> be sequences with <m>s_n\leq t_n,\forall n</m>.
              Suppose <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}s_n=s</m> and <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}t_n=t</m>.
              Prove <m>s\leq t</m>. 
              <hint>
                Assume for contradiction,
                that <m>s>t</m> and use the definition of convergence with
                <m>\eps=\frac{s-t}{2}</m> to produce an <m>n</m> with <m>s_n>t_n</m>.
              </hint>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that if a sequence converges, then its limit is unique.
              That is, prove that if <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}s_n=s</m> and <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}s_n=t</m>,
              then <m>s=t</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <idx><h>if the sequence <m>\left(s_n\right)</m> is bounded then
        <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\left(\frac{s_n}{n}\right)=0</m></h></idx> Prove that if the sequence
        <m>\left(s_n\right)</m> is bounded then <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\left(\frac{s_n}{n}\right)=0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem xml:id="prob_series-geometric">
    <statement>
      <p>
            <idx><h>series</h><h>Geometric series</h><h>convergence/divergence conditions for</h></idx>

        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that if <m>x\neq 1</m>, then
              <me>
                1+x+x^2+\cdots+x^n=\frac{1-x^{n+1}}{1-x}
              </me>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Use (a) to prove that if <m>|x|\lt 1</m>,
              then <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\left(\sum_{j=0}^nx^j\right)=\frac{1}{1-x}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <idx><h>limit</h><h> of ratios of polynomials</h></idx>
        Prove
        <me>
          \lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\frac{a_0+a_1n+a_2n^2+ \cdots+a_kn^k}{b_0+b_1n+b_2n^2+\cdots+b_kn^k}=\frac{a_k}{b_k}
        </me>,
        provided <m>b_k\neq 0</m>. [Notice that since a polynomial only has finitely many roots,
        then the denominator will be non-zero when <m>n</m> is sufficiently large.]
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
            <idx><h>sequences</h><h>difference of</h></idx>
            <idx><h>limit</h><h>of the difference of sequences</h></idx>
        Prove that if <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}s_n=s</m> and <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\left(s_n-t_n\right)=0</m>, then <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}t_n=s</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
            <idx><h>sequences</h><h>lower and upper bounds for</h></idx>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that if <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}s_n=s</m> and <m>s\lt t</m>,
              then there exists a real number <m>N</m> such that if <m>n>N</m> then <m>s_n\lt t</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that if <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}s_n=s</m> and <m>r\lt s</m>,
              then there exists a real number <m>M</m> such that if <m>n>M</m> then <m>r\lt s_n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem xml:id="prob_RatioTest">
    <statement>
      <p>
            <idx><h>sequences</h><h>Ratio Test for</h></idx>
            <idx><h>Ratio Test</h><h>for sequences</h></idx>
        Suppose <m>\left(s_n\right)</m> is a sequence of positive numbers such that
        <me>
          \lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\left(\frac{s_{n+1}}{s_n}\right)=L
        </me>.
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that if <m>L\lt 1</m>,
              then <m>\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}s_n=0</m>. 
              <hint> Choose <m>R</m> with <m>L\lt R\lt 1</m>.
                By the previous problem,
                <m>\exists</m> <m>N</m> such that if <m>n>N</m>,
                then <m>\frac{s_{n+1}}{s_n}\lt R</m>.
                Let <m>n_0>N</m> be fixed and show <m>s_{n_0+k}\lt R^ks_{n_0}</m>.
                Conclude that <m>\lim_{k\rightarrow\infty}s_{n_0+k}=0</m> and let <m>n=n_0+k</m>.
              </hint>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>c</m> be a positive real number.
              Prove <m>\displaystyle\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\left(\frac{c^n}{n!}\right)=0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>
</section>

